Lab: Stored XSS into anchor href attribute with double quotes HTML-encoded

Summary

This lab is vulnerable to Stored Cross-Site Scripting (Stored XSS) because attacker-controlled input is stored by the application and later inserted into the href attribute of an anchor (<a>) tag. Although double quotes are HTML-encoded, the application still allows a dangerous value such as a javascript: URI to be stored and rendered inside the link.

How the vulnerability works

The application takes user input and uses it as the value of an anchor tag’s href attribute, for example inside a website field or profile link. Since the value is stored and later rendered for other users, an attacker can submit a malicious URI instead of a normal URL.

Even though double quotes are encoded, that only prevents breaking out of the attribute using ". It does not stop XSS if the attacker can make the whole href value itself malicious.

Example rendered output:

<a href="javascript:alert(1)">Website</a>

When another user clicks the link, the JavaScript executes.

Payload

javascript:alert(1)

Why the payload works

The payload does not need to break out of the attribute. It directly becomes the href value. Because browsers treat javascript: as executable code inside links, clicking the link triggers the script.

Key point

This lab shows that HTML-encoding quotes is not enough if untrusted input is still allowed inside dangerous attributes like href. Input must be validated so only safe URL schemes such as http: or https: are allowed.
